The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 LOOSE CHANGE

 Tata Mutual Fund has launched Tata Mid Cap Fund, which will invest at least 65 per cent of its net assets in equity and equity-related instruments of mid-cap companies and up to 35 per cent in debt and money market instruments. The fund can also invest up to 35 per cent in other stocks. During the initial offer period, the fund will charge an entry load of 2.25 per cent on investments greater than Rs 5 lakh and less than Rs 2 crore. An exit load of 2 per cent is applicable on investments up to Rs 5 lakh if redeemed before 180 days and 0.25 per cent on Rs 2 crore to Rs 5 crore, if redeemed before 90 days from the date of allotment. The offer closes on June 15.

 Kotak Mahindra Old Mutual Life Insurance has declared a bonus of 6.75 per cent for its participatory contracts for the year ended March 31, 2005, an increase of almost 4 per cent over the previous year?s 6.5 per cent. 

 LIC Mutual Fund has changed the load structure on its equity, growth and opportunities fund. There will be no entry load up to Rs 1 lakh but an exit load of 2.25 per cent will be levied if the units are redeemed within two years of allotment. Applications more than Rs 1 lakh and up to Rs 1 crore will fetch an entry load of 2.25 per cent, but no exit load.




